Date: Tue, 23 Jan 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Bluetongue Serotype 8 Epidemic Bulletin
by EFSA Epidemiology Working Group;Bulletin 13, 19 Jan 2007 [edited].

Outbreak Period until 18 January, 2007: Main Observation
----------------------------------------------
The current bluetongue serotype 8 epidemic is now
into its 23rd week, with the case total having
risen to 2073 herds. Out of the 2072 cases with
correct georeferences, 695 cases were reported
from Belgium, 6 from France, 905 from Germany,
458 from the Netherlands, and 7 from Luxembourg.
[See additional data in commentary].
During the last 3 weeks new cases have continued
to be reported at a low level. This week's 8 new
cases occurred in cattle at the fringe of the
area known to be affected thus far. Most of the
new cases were detected through clinical case
reporting, but some were detected by serological
investigations prior to movements between zones
within Member States or between Member States.
Relative to the number of farms, the 2 areas that
have been most severely affected in 2006 are the
original cluster of cases where Belgium, Germany,
and the Netherlands share borders and the
Bergisches Land region of Germany. The latter is
not a cattle-dense region but now represents the
cluster with the largest spatial extent. However,
during 2006 the virus has also spread into or
close to areas with high cattle density in
Belgium, Germany, and the Netherlands.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[For the full report and to view all the maps,
see
<http://www.efsa.europa.eu/etc/medialib/efsa/in_focus/bluetongue.Par.0038.File.dat/bluetongue%20update%2019%20January%202007.pdf>.
According to the data included in table 1 of the
full report, "Number of cases reported by country
and by animal species affected", 8 new cases --
all in cattle -- have been reported through 18
Jan for the period between 12 and 18 Jan 2007 (7 in Germany, 1 in Luxembourg).
Out of the total 2072 fully documented BTV-8
outbreaks recorded since the beginning of the
panzootic in August/September 2006, 1062 involved
cattle, 951 small ruminants, 13 wild species and
46 mixed herds (herds including more than one susceptible species).
The continued occurrence of clinical cases during
the peak winter season is most unusual; for
clarification, entomological and epidemiological
research is required. - Mod.AS]
